Equations

  • $\mu$ is used for in-line equations
  • $$\mu$$ is used for equations

Lets assume that \(Y\) follows a normal distribution. \[Y \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma^2)\] Where we set in our simulations \(\mu = 10\) and \(\sigma^2 = 5\). We do something for every \(Y_i\).

Equations

  • $\mu$ is used for in-line equations
  • $$\mu$$ is used for equations

Lets assume that \(y\) is a vector with \(N\) elements such that \[y \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma^2),\] where we set in our simulations \(\mu = 10\) and \(\sigma^2 = 5\). We do something for every \(Y_i\) with \(i = 1, \dots, N\).
